    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Wait a minute, `PUSH3` is 3 bytes long, right?\r\nOn p. 28:\r\n`PUSH1` -> Place a 1-byte item on the stack\r\n`PUSH2` -> Place a 2-byte item on the stack\r\n...\r\n`PUSH32` -> Place a 32-byte item on the stack\r\n\r\nSo `PUSH3` -> Place a 3-byte item on the stack.\r\n\r\nBut you want to skip the data of a PUSH instruction, if any, so it needs to be one byte in the code after the end of the push instruction (to get to the first instruction after the PUSH instruction, if any).\r\n\r\nWhy not just `i + w + 1`? Is that not equal to and a simplified form of `i + w - PUSH1 + 2`?\r\n\r\nAh I know why.\r\n\r\nPUSH1 = 0x60, PUSH2 = 0x61, etc.\r\n\r\nSo if w = PUSH3 = 0x62, then\r\n`i + w - PUSH1 + 2 = i + 0x62 - 0x60 + 2 = i + 4`, which is the position we want, the first byte after the PUSH instruction.\r\n\r\nWhile `i + w + 1 = i + 0x62 + 1 = i + 0x63 <> i +4`.",
